media_caption: Balay Negrense Museum in Silay City, 2017
text_description: The Victor Fernandez Gaston heritage house in Silay, Negros Occidental, aka Balay Negrense, is built. It is now a house museum, marked by NHI in 1994. Photo: Balay Negrense Museum in Silay City, 2017 (Jennifer Flores Calica-Leonardo)

media_caption: Don Mariano Mercado House, ca 1990
text_description: The Nyor Mercado House in Carcar, Cebu is constructed. Photo: Don Mariano Mercado House, ca 1990 (Photo from CCP)

media_caption: Insular Ice Plant in Manila, ca 1920
text_description: The Insular Ice Plant and Cold Storage is built. Designed by Edgar Bourne in the Neoclassical style, it is made of brick and is located at the foot of Quiapo Bridge on the Pasig’s southern bank. It is demolished in 1984 to make way for LRT 1. Photo: Insular Ice Plant in Manila, ca 1920 (Edward Delos Santos/Pinoy Kollektor)

media_caption: The Manila Grand Opera House on Avenida Rizal, Manila ca 1920s
text_description: The Manila Grand Opera House in Manila is completed. Photo: Manila Grand Opera House, ca 1920 (Photo from CCP)

media_caption: Prewar cottages in Camp John Hay
text_description: A summer residence for the American commanding general is built in Camp John Hay. Photo: Prewar cottages in Camp John Hay, ca 1920 (Leo Cloma Collection)

media_caption: Manila City Hall, ca 1950
text_description: The Manila City Hall, designed by Antonio Toledo in the Neoclassical style, is completed. Photo: Manila City Hall, ca 1950 (Photo from CCP)

media_caption: San Miguel Corporation Building in Mandaluyong City, 2008
text_description: San Miguel Corporation (SMC) Head Office, designed by Francisco Mañosa, is completed. It is characterized as an environment friendly building, which minimizes the use of electricity. Photo: SMC Bldg in Mandaluyong City, 2008 (San Miguel Corporation)

media_caption: Balay na Tisa or Sarmiento-Osmeña bahay na bato in Carcar, Cebu, 2013, exemplifying arquitectura mestiza
text_description: The balay na tisa in Carcar, Cebu is built. It is declared heritage house by NHI on 4 Sep 2009. Photo: Balay na Tisa or Sarmiento-Osmeña bahay na bato, 2013 (Constantine Agustin)

media_caption: NONE
text_description: Federico Faura SJ establishes the Manila Observatory on the roof of the Jesuits’ Casa Mision in Intramuros.

media_caption: Manila Cathedral, ca 1910
text_description: The seventh Manila Cathedral is finished under the supervision of Arch Luciano Oliver. This cathedral in Neoromanesque style is bombed in 1945. Photo: Manila Cathedral, ca 1910 (Ortigas Foundation Library)

media_caption: Church of San Luis in Pampanga, 2005
text_description: Before this year, San Luis Church in Pampanga is completed. Photo: San Luis Church, 2005 (Franz Allan Rodriguez)

media_caption: La Insular Cigar Factory, ca 1920
text_description: La Insular Cigarette Factory, designed by Juan Jose Hervas in the Neomudejar style, is established beside the Binondo church. Photo: La Insular Cigar Factory, ca 1920 (Edward Delos Santos/Pinoy Kollektor)

media_caption: Taluksangay Mosque, built by the Nuño family
text_description: Taluksangay Mosque (in photo), built by Hadji Abdullah Maas Nuño, becomes a center of Islamic studies and jurisprudence.

media_caption: Manila Observatory on Padre Faura Street in Manila
media_credit: Photo from Philippine Picture Post Cards: 1900-1920 by Jonathan Best. The Bookmark, Inc, 1994.
text_description: Ruperto Ibañez designs the Neoclassical buildings for the Manila Observatory at Ermita. (Photo from Philippine Picture Post Cards: 1900-1920 by Jonathan Best. The Bookmark, Inc, 1994.)

media_caption: Train station in Tutuban, Manila
media_credit: Photo from Philippine Picture Post Cards: 1900-1920 by Jonathan Best, The Bookmark, Inc, 1994
text_description: Tutuban Railroad Station in Manila, is completed. It uses refabricated steel parts manufactured in England. Photo: Tutuban train station (Photo from Philippine Picture Post Cards: 1900-1920 by Jonathan Best, The Bookmark, Inc, 1994)

media_caption: Hotel de Oriente
media_credit: Photo colorized by Eduardo S. Sison, John Tewell Collection
text_description: Hotel el Oriente (in photo), facing Plaza Calderon in Binondo and designed by Juan Hervas, opens. It is the first modern hotel in Manila, with running hot and cold shower and in suite bathrooms, electricity, telephone service, and a restaurant that serves international cuisine. (Photo colorized by Eduardo S. Sison, John Tewell Collection)

media_caption: Goldenberg Mansion facade in Manila, 2011
text_description: The Goldenberg Mansion in San Miguel, Manila is constructed. During martial law (1972-1981), it is refurbished and used as a Malacañan guest house in the San Miguel district. Photo: Goldenberg Mansion facade, 2011 (National Historical Commission of the Philippines)

media_caption: Lazi Convento, ca 1990
text_description: The Lazi Convento of the Recollects in Lazi, Siqujor, is completed. The convento has the reputation of being the largest in the Philippines. Photo: Lazi Convento, ca 1990 (Photo from CCP)

media_caption: Manila Observatory on Padre Faura Street in Manila
media_credit: Philippine Picture Post Cards: 1900-1920 by Jonathan Best, The Bookmark, Inc, 1994
text_description: An astronomical observatory is completed at Ermita (Padre Faura St.) for the Manila Observatory (in photo). (Philippine Picture Post Cards: 1900-1920 by Jonathan Best, The Bookmark, Inc, 1994)

media_caption: Cape Bojeador Lighthouse in Ilocos Norte, 2013
text_description: The Cape Bojeador Lighthouse in Burgos, Ilocos Norte is completed. Photo: Cape Bojeador Lighthouse, 2013 (Emir Sicangco)

media_caption: Casa Redonda, rebuilt according to the plans of the original octagonal hut by Jose Rizal
text_description: Jose Rizal builds houses in Talisay, Dapitan, Zamboanga del Norte. He builds a residence, a school, and the casa redonda, an octagonal house for a clinic. Then he begins the waterworks for Talisay with the assistance of Bro. Juan Costa SJ in preparation for his model farm which will use modern methods of agriculture.

media_caption: Stage, orchestra, and balconies of the Teatro Zorrilla, Calle Azcaragga (now Claro M. Recto Avenue), Manila, 1911, where operas, sarsuwela, concerts, and other musical events were held in the first decades of the American period
text_description: Teatro Circo Zorrilla on Calzada de Iris (now C. M. Recto) is inaugurated. Photo: Teatro Zorrilla, 1911 (Filipinas Heritage Library)

media_caption: Church of Santo Tomas Villanueva in Pardo, Cebu, ca 1990
text_description: Pardo Church in Cebu, commenced in 1880, is completed. Photo: Pardo Church, 1990 (Photo from CCP)

media_caption: Lourdes Church after World War II
text_description: The Capuchin Church of Nuestra Señora de Lourdes in the Romanesque Revival style in Intramuros is completed.The church is damaged during World War II and not rebuilt. The Capuchins rebuild in Quezon City after World War II. (Photo from CCP)

media_caption: American-period Silliman Hall of Silliman University in Dumaguete City
text_description: Silliman Hall in Silliman University in Dumaguete City is built. Photo: American-period Silliman Hall of Silliman University in Dumaguete City (Nicanor G. Tiongson Collection)

media_caption: Church of Santiago
text_description: Dapitan Church of Santiago in Zamboanga del Norte is completed. Photo: Church of Santiago (Carmelo Bayarcal)

media_caption: Kennon Road to Baguio, popularly known as the Zigzag, ca 1915
text_description: Kennon Road is completed, as are the lagoon in Burnham Park and the Baguio Country Club, the latter in Stick-style using wood and thatch. Photo: Kennon Road, ca 1915 (John Tewell Collection)

media_caption: Yap-Sandiego Ancestral House, 2004
text_description: Yap house in Carcar, Cebu is constructed, later renovated in 1936. Photo: Yap-Sandiego Ancestral House, 2004 (Wikimedia Commons)

media_caption: American-period Central United Methodist Church
text_description: Central United Methodist Church on T. M. Kalaw is built, designed by Juan Arellano. Photo: American-period Central United Methodist Church (Leo Cloma Collection)

media_caption: Prewar Mansion House
text_description: The Mansion House in Baguio (in photo), designed by William E. Parsons in the Neoclassical style and constructed as official summer residence of American governor general, is completed. And so are Baguio General Hospital; 80 residential cottages at government center in Baguio; and Baguio Market. (Photo from Edward Delos Santos/Pinoy Kollektor)

media_caption: American-period Mirador Hill
text_description: The Jesuits build a house on top of Mirador Hill; one wing is used by the Manila Observatory. Photo: American-period Mirador Hill (Leo Cloma Collection)

media_caption: American-period Army and Navy Club in Manila
text_description: The Army-Navy Club at the Luneta, designed by William E. Parsons, is completed. Photo: American-period Army and Navy Club (Leo Cloma Collection)

media_caption: Baguio City Hall, ca 1925
text_description: The Baguio Government Complex is built using wood. The Baguio City Hall is completed in the Stick-style. Photo: Baguio City Hall, ca 1925 (Ben Cabrera Collection)

media_caption: Prewar YMCA Building in Manila
text_description: YMCA Manila, designed by William Parsons, is built. Photo: Prewar YMCA Building in Manila (Leo Cloma Collection)

media_caption: Prewar Philippine General Hospital in Manila
text_description: The Philippine General Hospital, designed by William Parsons in the Mission Revival style, is completed. Photo: Prewar Philippine General Hospital in Manila (Leo Cloma Collection)

media_caption: Elks Club at the foreground and Army and Navy Club at the background before World War II
text_description: Elks Club in Luneta, Manila, designed by William Parsons, is completed. Photo: Prewar Elks Club (Leo Cloma Collection)

media_caption: Prewar Manila Hotel
text_description: Manila Hotel, designed by William Parsons and begun in 1909, is inaugurated. Photo: Prewar Manila Hotel (Leo Cloma Collection)

media_caption: Don Francisco Barrios residence, built in the 1860s, now Bank of the Philippine Islands Zamboanga main office, 2017
text_description: BPI opens branch at Zamboanga at the ground floor of a house built by Don Francisco Barrios in the 1870s and renovated as the official residence of Gov Maj John “Black Jack” Pershing. Photo: Former Pershing residence repurposed as the main office of BPI Zamboanga, 2017 (Eduardo Flores Jr)

media_caption: Bradford Memorial Church, ca 1913-24, Cebu City
media_credit: Cebuano Studies Center, University of San Carlos
text_description: Bradford Memorial Church is completed in Neogothic style. It is the oldest Protestant church in Cebu. It is restored in 2013. Photo: American-period Bradford Memorial Church in Cebu City (Cebuano Studies Center, University of San Carlos)

media_caption: Banaue Rice Terraces, ca 1990
text_description: The rice terraces in Bunghalian, Ifugao are constructed.

media_caption: Convention Center in Iloilo City, built in 2015
text_description: The Iloilo Convention Center (in photo) in Manduriao, designed by William Coscolluela, is completed for the APEC convention in November. (Photo from Iloilo Business Park)

media_caption: Zuellig Building, the first LEED-certified “green” high-rise building in the Philippines, 2016
text_description: The Zuellig Bldg in Makati, begun in 2008 and designed by William Coscolluela, is completed. It is the first building in the Philippines to receive LEED’s platinum certification as a “green building.” Photo: Zuellig Building, 2016 (Kiko del Rosario)

media_caption: Art noveau Mariano Uy-Chaco Building, built 1914, now Philtrust Bank Building in Escolta
text_description: The Uy Chaco (now Philtrust) Bldg in the art noveau style, in Binondo, is completed. (Photo from CCP)

media_caption: El Hogar building, ca 1920
text_description: El Hogar is inaugurated. Photo: El Hogar, ca 1920 (Photo from CCP)

media_caption: Prewar Gotiaoco Building
media_credit: Sugbu Chinese Heritage Museum, Ortigas Foundation Library Collection
text_description: Gotiaoco Bldg is completed. It is the first building in Cebu to have an elevator. Photo: Prewar Gotiaoco Building (Sugbu Chinese Heritage Museum, Ortigas Foundation Library Collection)

media_caption: American-period Philippine Normal School in Manila
text_description: The Philippine Normal School (now PNU), designed by William Parsons, is built in the Mission revival and Neoclassical styles. Photo: American-period Philippine Normal School (Leo Cloma Collection)

media_caption: Dominican Hill
text_description: The Dominican residence, begun in 1913 and designed by Roque Ruaño OP is completed on Dominican Hill, Baguio. In 1973 the Dominicans sell the property and it becomes Diplomat Hotel. In 2005, the ruined building and property is acquired by Baguio City and is renamed Heritage and Nature Park. The house is marked by NHCP in 2014. (Photo from Edward Delos Santos/Pinoy Kollektor)

media_caption: Prewar Legislative Building in Manila
text_description: The National Library, designed by Ralph Doane and Antonio Toledo, is completed. Appropriated for use by the Philippine Legislature in 1926, Juan Arellano renovates the building. Badly damaged during World War II, it is restored but with less opulence. Photo: Prewar Legislative Building (Edward Delos Santos/Pinoy Kollektor)

media_caption: Pangasinan Capitol Building in Lingayen City, 1990
text_description: The Lingayen Provincial Capitol in Pangasinan, begun in 1917 and designed by Ralph Doane, is completed. In Neoclassical style, it is noted for its Grecian temple facade with Ionic columns. (Photo from CCP)

media_caption: Luneta Hotel to the left and Bayview Hotel to the right before World War II
text_description: Luneta Hotel, designed by Salvador Ferre in the French Renaissance style, is completed. It is characterized by a Mansard roof. It survives World War II and functions as a hotel until it is closed in 1987. It is marked by the NHCP in 2014. Photo: Luneta Hotel to the left and Bayview Hotel to the right before World War II.

media_caption: Leyte Capitol in Tacloban City, ca 1990
text_description: Antonio Toledo designs UP College of Medicine Annex and University Library, and the Leyte Capitol. Photo: Leyte Capitol, ca 1990 (Nicanor G. Tiongson Collection)

media_caption: Saint Catherine’s Academy in Carcar, Cebu, ca 1990
text_description: St Catherine’s Academy (P. del Corro Bldg) in Carcar, Cebu is completed.

media_caption: Church of San Diego, ca 1990
text_description: The Church of San Diego in Silay, Negros Occidental, is designed in Neoromanesque and Renaissance styles by the Italian architect Lucio Verasconi. Photo: Church of San Diego, ca 1990 (Photo from CCP)

media_caption: Lopez Mansion or Nelly Garden in Iloilo City, 2012
text_description: Nelly Garden, aka the Lopez-Hofileña mansion, in Jaro, Iloilo is completed. Photo: Nelly Garden, 2012 (Kimberly Chafe)

media_caption: The dispensary in Carcar, now a museum, 2016
text_description: Carcar Dispensary, now the Carcar Museum, is completed. Photo: Carcar Museum, 2016 (Karl Alfred Jamandre)

media_caption: Perez-Samanillo Building, behind bahay na bato on the right, in prewar Escolta
text_description: The Perez-Samanillo Bldg, begun in 1928 and designed by Andres Luna de San Pedro, is completed. Photo: Perez-Samanillo Building, behind bahay na bato on the right, in prewar Escolta (Leo Cloma Collection)

media_caption: 1930 Insular Life Building in Binondo
media_credit: Archives of The Insular Life Assurance Company, Ltd; National Library of the Philippines Collection
text_description: Insular Life Bldg is completed in Binondo, designed by William James Odom and Fernando de la Cantera. Photo: 1930 Insular Life Building (Archives of The Insular Life Assurance Company, Ltd; National Library of the Philippines Collection)

media_caption: American-period Central Post Office in Manila
media_credit: University of the Philippines Main Library Collection
text_description: The Central Post Office on Liwasang Bonifacio, Manila, designed by Juan Arellano and Tomas Mapua, is completed. (University of the Philippines Main Library Collection)

media_caption: Metropolitan Theater, ca 1930
media_credit: Colorized by Bilog Bilugan, John Tewell Collection
text_description: Metropolitan Theater in Manila is inaugurated. Its architects, Juan and Otilio Arellano, design it in Art Deco. Its sculptures are by Francesco Monti and paintings by Fernando Amorsolo. Photo: Metropolitan Theater, ca 1930 (Colorized by Bilog Bilugan, John Tewell Collection)

media_caption: Ideal and State Theaters along Avenida Rizal, Manila
text_description: The Ideal Theater on Rizal Ave, Manila, designed by Pablo Antonio, is completed. Photo: Ideal and State Theaters along Avenida Rizal, Manila (Leo Cloma Collection)

media_caption: Maria Ledesma Golez House in Silay City after restoration
text_description: The Angel Araneta Ledesma house and the Maria Golez house, both in Silay, Negros Occidental, are completed. Photo: Maria Ledesma Golez House after restoration (Rob Sampang)

media_caption: Central Seminary Building of the University of Santo Tomas, ca 1940
text_description: UST Central Seminary, designed by Fernando H. Ocampo in Art Deco, is completed. Photo: UST Central Seminary, ca 1940 (Colorized by Kiko del Rosario)

media_caption: Municipal Hall of Jaro, Iloilo, restored in 2017 by the National Museum
text_description: The Art Deco Jaro Municipal building, designed by Juan Arellano, is completed. It is restored in 2017 as the National Museum of the Philippines regional office. (Photo by Kelvin Tagnipez)

media_caption: Prewar art deco-style Rizal Memorial Stadium in Manila
text_description: The Rizal Memorial Stadium in Art Deco on Vito Cruz (Pablo Ocampo) St, designed by the Bureau of Public Works, is completed. Begun in 1932, it is built for the Far Eastern Championship Games, forerunner of the ASEAN Games. (Leo Cloma Collection)

media_caption: Cathedral of Our Lady of the Atonement
text_description: The Baguio Church of Our Lady of the Atonement on Kampo Hill, officially named cathedral in 1935, is completed this year. It is predominantly Neogothic although Roman arches are used in the facade and bell tower. Florimund Carlu CICM is responsible for the project. (Photo from Nicanor G. Tiongson)

media_caption: Caida and sala of the Lizares House in Talisay, Negros Occidental, ca 1990
text_description: The Lizares-Alunan residence in Talisay, Negros Occidental is completed. Photo: Caida and sala of the Lizares House, ca 1990. (Photo from CCP)

media_caption: De La Salle College before World War II
text_description: De La Salle University, designed by Tomas Mapua in the Neoclassical style, is completed. (Leo Cloma Collection)

media_caption: Cebu Provincial Capitol, 2016
text_description: The Cebu Provincial Capitol is completed. Designed by Toledo in the Stripped Classicism variation of Art Deco, it is the terminus of a wide avenue. Photo: Cebu Provincial Capitol, 2016 (Cebu Provincial Government)

media_caption: View of Osmeña Ave with the Rizal Library, left, and the Cebu Provincial Capitol at far end, ca 1950
text_description: The Jose Rizal Memorial Library is constructed in Cebu, along Osmeña Ave. It is Neorenaissance with an elevated logia. Photo: View of Osmeña Ave with the Rizal Library, left, and the Cebu Provincial Capitol at far end, ca 1950 (Leo Cloma Collection)

media_caption: Jai-Alai Building in Manila, 1952
text_description: Jai-Alai, in Streamline Moderne style, is completed, designed by the American architects, Walter C. Wurdeman and Welton David Becket. Photo: Jai-Alai Building in Manila, 1952 (www.skyscrapercity.com)

media_caption: Adamson University, ca 1950
text_description: Adamson University, founded in 1932, transfers to new buildings at San Marcelino campus. Photo: Adamson University, ca 1950 (Colorized by Kiko del Rosario)

media_caption: Former city hall of Iloilo, now the University of the Philippines Visayas
media_credit: The University of the Philippines: A University for Filipinos, edited by Gloria D. Feliciano. Diamond Jubilee Presidential Commission, 1984
text_description: The former Iloilo City Hall, built 1933 to 1935, is turned over to UP Iloilo (now UP Visayas) by Fernando Lopez. Photo: UP Visayas, 1980s (The University of the Philippines: A University for Filipinos, edited by Gloria D. Feliciano. Diamond Jubilee Presidential Commission, 1984)

media_caption: Chapel of the Holy Sacrifice in the University of the Philippines Diliman, showing its thin-shell concrete dome, 1989
text_description: The UP Chapel of the Holy Sacrifice, planned in 1947, is completed. It is a modernist church, designed by Leandro V. Locsin with artworks by Arturo Luz, Vicente Manansala, and Napoleon “Billy” Abueva. Photo: UP Chapel with its thin-shell concrete dome, 1989 (Photo from CCP)

media_caption: Araneta Coliseum in Cubao, Quezon City, ca 1960
text_description: The Araneta Coliseum, begun in 1957, is completed. Called the “Big Dome,” its architect is Dominador Lacson Lugtu and engineer is Leonardo Onjunco Lugtu. Photo: Araneta Coliseum, ca 1960 (Way Kurat)

media_caption: Philippine-American Life Insurance Company Building in Manila, built in 1961
text_description: The Philam Life Insurance Bldg on Isaac Peral Ave (later United Nations Ave), designed by Carlos Arguelles, is completed. (Photo from CCP)

media_caption: Western side facade of the Coconut Palace
text_description: The Coconut Palace, aka Tahanang Pilipino, designed by Francisco Mañosa, is completed. It is renovated in 2010 and becomes the official residence and office of the vice-president. Photo: Coconut Palace, western side facade (Mañosa & Company, Inc.)

media_caption: Chapel of the Monastery of the Transfiguration in Malaybalay, Bukidnon, 2017
text_description: The Benedictine Monastery and Chapel of the Transfiguration, designed by Leandro Locsin in Malaybalay, Bukidnon, is completed. This is Locsin’s last major work. Photo: Chapel of the Transfiguration, 2017 (Nerissa Casalta Cabaña)

media_caption: Pacific Star Building in Makati City, 1991
text_description: Various high rise office and multiuse buildings are completed, namely: Pacific Star (in photo) in Makati City, designed by Gabriel Formoso, as a pioneer in post-modern architecture, Tower One of the Makati Stock Exchange, designed by Leandro Locsin and SOM, and King’s Court II also in Makati, designed by Rogelio Villarosa. (Photo from CCP)

media_caption: Cathedral Museum of Cebu, 2013
text_description: The restoration of the Cebu rectory under Arch Melva Hava begins. The 19th century bahay na bato is reused as the Cathedral Museum of Cebu. Photo: Cathedral Museum of Cebu, 2013 (Constantine Agustin)

media_caption: Church of the Gesù inside the Ateneo de Manila University campus, 2017
text_description: Ateneo de Manila University’s Church of the Gesù, designed by Jose Recio and Carmelo Casas, is completed. Photo: Church of the Gesù, 2017 (Kiko del Rosario)

media_caption: Sheik Karimul Makdum Mosque, in Simunul, Tawi-Tawi, known as the oldest mosque in the country, 2010
text_description: Attributed to Makhdum, the first mosque in the Philippines is built on Simunul Island, Tawi-tawi. (Fung Yu, www.pamana.ph)

media_caption: NONE
text_description: Following the Renaissance grid plan, the city of Manila is laid out by Miguel Lopez de Legazpi. At this point the walls that will characterize Manila are not yet built; instead the palisaded enclosure of Fort Santiago is built at the site of Rajah Sulayman’s kuta, while the rest of the city has no defenses.

media_caption: Calle Real in Intramuros flanked on the left by San Agustin Monastery and on the right by the Augustinian Provincial House
text_description: The Augustinians establish the Monasterio de San Pablo, popularly known as San Agustín, at the site alotted them by Legazpi, along Calle Real (in photo). (Leo Cloma Collection)

media_caption: Fort Santiago, ca 1920
text_description: The first provisional fortifications of Manila and Fort Santiago are built. Photo: Fort Santiago, ca 1920 (Nicanor G. Tiongson Collection)

media_caption: NONE
text_description: During the reconstruction of Manila shortly after the fire, the first example of the bahay na bato is built, a work by Antonio Sedeño and Bp Domingo de Salazar, who rebuild the bishop’s house in stone and wood.

media_caption: NONE
text_description: Intramuros’ first stone defense, Nuestra Señora de Guia tower, is constructed by Antonio Sedeño at the southwestern corner of the city of Manila.

media_caption: NONE
text_description: A stone convento is built in Malate by the Augustinians.

media_caption: NONE
text_description: Gov-Gen Perez Dasmariñas rebuilds Fort Santiago, raising a stone wall along the shore connecting Santiago and the tower Nuestra Señora de Guia. The walls of Intramuros are rebuilt, reinforced, renovated over the centuries and until 1862.

media_caption: Church of Santo Domingo in Intramuros, Manila, ca 1910
NONE
text_description: The Church of Santa Ana in Intramuros is completed. It is the first Renaissance-Baroque church built in the Philippines.The church’s stone vault collapses during the 1600 earthquake. It is subsequently demolished in 1626 to make room for the first San Ignacio church..

media_caption: Prewar Antipolo Church and Convent
media_credit: Photo from Our New Possessions by Trumbull White, John E. Hoham & Co, 1898
text_description: Antipolo is turned over to the Jesuits by the Franciscans. Antipolo has a church, convento, schools for boys and girls, hospital, and lots marked out on a grid plan for native dwellings. Photo: Prewar Antipolo Church and Convent (Our New Possessions by Trumbull White, John E. Hoham & Co, 1898)

media_caption: San Agustin Church in Intramuros, Manila, 1993
media_credit: Photo by Betty Lalana and Lino Arboleda, Ortigas Foundation Library Collection
text_description: San Agustin Church and monastery in Intramuros, begun in 1586, are completed. Designed by architect Juan Macias, the church is closer in style to the Renaissance. Photo: San Agustin Church, 1993 (Betty Lalana and Lino Arboleda, Ortigas Foundation Library)

media_caption: Spanish-period Fort San Felipe in Cavite
text_description: Fort San Felipe, Cavite, is built. In the early 20th century, Americans demolish it to build a naval base, but retain the fort’s gate and the flanking curtain walls.

media_caption: Shrine of Our Lady of Caysasay, 2017
text_description: The Augustinian shrine church to Our Lady of Caysasay, Taal, Batangas, is built. Photo: Shrine of Our Lady of Caysasay, 2017 (Kiko del Rosario)

media_caption: Facade of Morong Church in Rizal with classical columns, 1991
text_description: Morong church in Laguna is completed. Its facade is renovated in the 19th century, following the design of Bartolome Palatino, a master builder from Paete, Laguna. Photo: Facade of Morong Church, 1991

media_caption: Fort San Pedro, demolished in the 1900s
text_description: Fort San Pedro in Iloilo is built as defense against the Dutch. (Photo from Leo Cloma)

media_caption: Facade of Church of San Gregorio Magno in Majayjay, Laguna, 1993
media_credit: Photo by Betty Lalana and Lino Arboleda, Ortigas Foundation Library Collection
text_description: Majayjay church, begun ca 1616, is completed. It is reconstructed around 1707. It is the largest Franciscan church and convento in Laguna. Photo: Majayjay Church, 1993 (Betty Lalana and Lino Arboleda, Ortigas Foundation Library)

media_caption: Puente de España, ca 1920, later replaced by Jones Bridge
text_description: Puente Grande de España is completed. Spanning the Pasig and connecting Intramuros with Binondo, its last reconstruction and repair is in the 19th century. Photo: Puente de España, ca 1920 (John Tewell Collection)

media_caption: Ruins of the first San Ignacio Church, ca 1880
media_credit: Photo by Francisco Van Camp, John Tewell Collection
text_description: The first San Ignacio church at Calle Real del Palacio, begun in 1626, is completed. It is designed in the Baroque style by the Italian Gianantonio Campioni SJ. Photo: Ruins of the first San Ignacio Church, ca 1880 (Photo by Francisco Van Camp, John Tewell Collection)

media_caption: Prewar Antipolo Church and Convent (Our New Possessions by Trumbull White. John E. Hoham & Co, 1898.)
media_credit: Photo from Our New Possessions by Trumbull White, John E. Hoham & Co, 1898
text_description: Antipolo church in Rizal, begun in 1630 and designed by Juan de Salazar SJ, is completed. It houses the black image of the Nuestra Señora de la Paz y Buenviaje, given to the church in 1632. Photo: Prewar Antipolo Church and Convent (Our New Possessions by Trumbull White. John E. Hoham & Co, 1898)

media_caption: Outer walls of Fort Pilar
text_description: Fort San Jose (later renamed Pilar) in Zamboanga is built by Melchor de Vera SJ. It is demolished in 1663, when the Spanish garrison is called to Manila to meet the threat of an attack by Koxinga. Photo: Outer walls of Fort Pilar (Wikimedia Commons)

media_caption: Church of the Nuestra Señora de Candelaria in Silang, Cavite, 1994
media_credit: Photo by Betty Lalana and Lino Arboleda, Ortigas Foundation Library Collection
text_description: Silang’s Church of Nuestra Señora de Candelaria is completed under the supervision of Juan Salazar SJ. Its Baroque retablos are designated as a National Treasure by the National Museum in 2016. Photo: Silang Church, 1994 (Betty Lalana and Lino Arboleda, Ortigas Foundation Library)

media_caption: Colegio de San Juan de Letran, 1887
text_description: The Dominicans complete a school building for 200 students for Letran. Made of stone, it is located near the Church of Santo Domingo. Acquiring a lot at the corner of the Baluarte de San Gabriel in 1688, Letran moves to this site, where it has remained since. Photo: Colegio de San Juan de Letran, 1887 (John Tewell Collection)

media_caption: Church of San Pedro y San Pablo in Loboc, Bohol, 2003
media_credit: Photo by Betty Lalana and Lino Arboleda, Ortigas Foundation Library Collection
text_description: The first stone church of Loboc, Bohol. is completed around this year. Photo: Church of San Pedro y San Pablo in Loboc, Bohol, 2003 (Betty Lalana and Lino Arboleda, Ortigas Foundation Library)

media_caption: Church and Fort of San Agustin in Cuyo, Palawan, 2005
media_credit: Photos by Betty Lalana and Lino Arboleda, Ortigas Foundation Library Collection
text_description: Cuyo church and fort in Palawan are completed by Juan de San Severo, OAR.

media_caption: Church of San Agustin in Paoay, Ilocos Norte, 2012
media_credit: Photo by Betty Lalana and Lino Arboleda, Ortigas Foundation Library Collection
text_description: Pao-ay church, Ilocos Norte is started. It takes a long time to complete. It is reinaugurated in 1896, when work on the ceiling paintings is completed. Photo: Paoay Church, 2012 (Betty Lalana and Lino Arboleda, Ortigas Foundation Library)

media_caption: Church of Nuestra Señora de la Asuncion in Maragondon, Cavite, 1994
media_credit: Photo by Betty Lalana and Lino Arboleda, Ortigas Foundation Library Collection
text_description: Maragondon’s Church of La Asuncion de la Virgen in Cavite and the Santa Cruz church in Marinduque are completed. Photo: Maragondon Church, 1994 (Betty Lalana and Lino Arboleda, Ortigas Foundation Library)

media_caption: Church of Santa Maria Magdalena in Kawit, Cavite, 1994
media_credit: Photo by Betty Lalana and Lino Arboleda, Ortigas Foundation Library Collection
text_description: Completed this year are the Kawit Church of Santa Maria Magdalena in Cavite, the Santa Cruz church in Manila, and the Cainta Church of Nuestra Señora de la Luz in Rizal. Photo: Kawit Church, 1994 (Betty Lalana and Lino Arboleda, Ortigas Foundation Library)

media_caption: Facade of the Church of Santiago in Paete, Laguna, 1993
media_credit: Photo by Betty Lalana and Lino Arboleda, Ortigas Foundation Library Collection
text_description: Paete Church of Santiago in Laguna is completed. Photo: Paete Church, 1993 (Betty Lalana and Lino Arboleda, Ortigas Foundation Library)

media_caption: Church of the Inmaculada Concepcion in Guiuan, Eastern Samar, 2016
text_description: The Guiuan Church of La Inmaculada Concepcion in Samar, probably the second and more permanent church, is completed around this year. Photo: Guiuan Church, 2016 (Kinna G. Kwan)

media_caption: Inner plaza of Fort Pilar, Zamboanga City, 2009
text_description: Fort Pilar in Zamboanga is built by military architect Juan de Ciscara at the site of Fort San Jose; which demolished in 1663. Photo: Inner plaza of Fort Pilar, Zamboanga City, 2009 (Eldon Tenorio)

media_caption: Church of the Inmaculada Concepcion in Baclayon, Bohol, 2012
text_description: Baclayon Church of La Inmaculada Concepcion in Bohol is completed around this time. It is damaged by the 2013 earthquake but is subsequently restored. Photo: Baclayon Church, 2012 (Wikimedia Commons)

media_caption: Jesuit House of 1730 in Cebu City, 2015
media_credit: Photo from Ramon Aboitiz Foundation Inc Collection
text_description: The Jesuit house at Zulueta St, Parian district, Cebu is completed. It is the oldest dated bahay na bato in Cebu. Photo: Jesuit House, 2015 (Ramon Aboitiz Foundation Inc)

media_caption: Loboc Church, Bohol, May 1990
text_description: The second Loboc Church of San Pedro y San Pablo in Bohol is completed.

media_caption: NONE
article_title: Architecture 1735 Fort San Pedro, Cebu renovated
text_description: Fort San Pedro in Cebu is renovated. The site is said to be the place where Legazpi had built a triangular palisade in 1565.

media_caption: Church of San Luis Obispo de Tolosa in Lucban, Quezon, 2013
text_description: Lucban Church is completed. Photo: Lucban Church, 2013 (Mariano Sayno)

media_caption: Prewar Ayuntamiento or City Hall in Intramuros
media_credit: Philippine Picture Post Cards: 1900-1920 by Jonathan Best, The Bookmark, Inc, 1994
text_description: The second Ayuntamiento or city hall of Manila is completed. Photo: Prewar Ayuntamiento or City Hall in Intramuros (Philippine Picture Post Cards: 1900-1920 by Jonathan Best, The Bookmark, Inc, 1994)

media_caption: Basilica Minore of the Santo Niño
media_credit: Photo from Cebuano Studies Center, University of San Carlos
text_description: The Church of the Santo Niño (presently Basilica Minore del Santo Niño) in Cebu is completed under Juan de Albarran OSA. Photo: Basilica Minore of the Santo Niño (Cebuano Studies Center, University of San Carlos)

media_caption: San Francisco Church, destroyed during World War II
text_description: Church of Nuestra Señora de los Angeles (in photo), more popularly known as San Francisco in Intramuros, is constructed. The church is destroyed during World War II. (Leo Cloma Collection)

media_caption: NONE
text_description: A stone church built by the Franciscans in 1600 in Tayabas, Quezon is ruined by earthquake, most likely a consequence of Mt. Banahaw’s eruption.

media_caption: Augustinian-built Church of San Juan de Sahagun in Tigbauan, Iloilo, 2007
media_credit: Photo by Betty Lalana and Lino Aroleda, Ortigas Foundation Library Collection
text_description: The Augustinian Church of San Juan de Sahagun in Tigbauan, Iloilo with its unique plateresque façade is completed around this time. Photo: San Juan de Sahagun Church, 2007 (Betty Lalana and Lino Arboleda, Ortigas Foundation Library)

media_caption: Church of San Bartolome Apostol in Nagcarlan, Laguna, 1993
media_credit: Photo by Betty Lalana and Lino Arboleda, Ortigas Foundation Library Collection
text_description: Nagcarlan Church in Laguna church is completed. Photo: Church of San Bartolome Apostol in Nagcarlan, Laguna, 1993 (Betty Lalana and Lino Arboleda, Ortigas Foundation Library)

media_caption: Church of San Pedro y San Pablo in Calasiao, Pangasinan, 2014
text_description: Calasiao church in Pangasinan, begun in 1753, is most likely completed this year. Photo: Church of San Pedro y San Pablo in Calasiao, Pangasinan, 2014 (Tony Rivera)

media_caption: Gate and walls of Fort San Antonio Abad in Manila, 1990, top
text_description: Fort San Antonio Abad is constructed after the British leave. It replaces an earlier fort used as the polverin or gunpowder depot, which is previously located inside Intramuros. Photo: Gate and walls of Fort San Antonio Abad in Manila, 1990

media_caption: Church of San Pedro de Alcantara and Diocesan Shrine of Nuestra Señora de los Dolores de Turumba in Pakil, Laguna, 2016
text_description: Pakil’s Church of San Diego Alcantara in Laguna is completed. It is the site of the seven fiestas of Nuestra Señora de Dolores, known for the Turumba. Photo: Pakil Church, 2016 (Vonna Vista)

media_caption: Cathedral of San Pedro in Tuguegarao in Cagayan, 2003
media_credit: Photo by Betty Lalana and Lino Arboleda, Ortigas Foundation Library Collection
text_description: Tuguegarao Church of Santo Domingo in Cagayan, begun in 1762, is completed.

media_caption: Interior of the Church of Santiago Apostol in Betis, Pampanga, 2016
text_description: The Church of Santiago in Betis, Pampanga is completed. Photo: Interior of the Church of Santiago Apostol in Betis, Pampanga, 2016 (Cereneo Mistal)

media_caption: NONE
text_description: Daraga Church of Nuestra Señora de Porteria in Albay begins construction.

media_caption: Church of Santa Monica in Pan-ay, Capiz, 2013
media_credit: Photo by Betty Lalana and Lino Arboleda, Ortigas Foundation Library Collection
text_description: The second Pan-ay Church of Santa Monica in Capiz is completed; it replaces an earlier church, constructed ca 1692. The second church is reconstructed in 1884. Photo: Church of Santa Monica in Pan-ay, Capiz, 2013 (Betty Lalana and Lino Arboleda, Ortigas Foundation Library)

media_caption: Church of Nuestra Señora del Patrocinio de Maria in Boljoon, Cebu, 2009
media_credit: National Historical Commission of the Philippines Collection
text_description: Church of the Patrocinio in Boljoon, Cebu is constructed. Rococo motifs are evident on the retablo, considered an exemplary of this style. Photo: Boljoon Church, 2009 (National Historical Commission of the Philippines)

media_caption: Holy Rosary Minor Seminary in Naga City, 2003
media_credit: Photo by Betty Lalana and Lino Arboleda, Ortigas Foundation Library Collection
text_description: The Casa de Clerigos and Seminario Conciliar, later known as Holy Rosary Seminary, in Naga is constructed around this time.

media_caption: Facade of the Church of San Matias in Tumauini, Isabela, 2007
media_credit: Photo by Betty Lalana and Lino Arboleda, Ortigas Foundation Library Collection
text_description: The brick church of San Matias in Tumauini, Isabela starts construction, supposedly under friar-architect, Antonio Lobato OP. Photo: Tumauini Church, 2007 (Betty Lalana and Lino Arboleda, Ortigas Foundation Library)

media_caption: Church of San Ildefonso in Tanay, Rizal, 2012
text_description: The Tanay Church of San Idelfonso in Rizal is completed. Its altars are Rococo. Photo: Tanay Church, 2012 (www.juan-ted.com)

media_caption: Restored Casa de Comunidad de Tayabas in Quezon, 2011
text_description: The Casa de Communidad in Tayabas, Quezon is built of stone under Gob Salvador Flores de San Francisco. It is repaired in 1810 by Gov Lorenzo de los Reyes, then remodelled and expanded in 1831-1835 by Gov Diego Enriquez. Photo: Restored Casa de Comunidad de Tayabas, 2011 (Romnick Coros)

media_caption: NONE
text_description: The Real Audiencia, formerly housed in the Palacio del Gobernador, acquires its own property in Intramuros. Soon after the Audiencia building is started.

media_caption: Main facade of the Malacañan Palace, ca 1920
text_description: Malacañan is built by Don Antonia Dias Conde around this year; later it is bought by Luis Rocha in 1796; then by Jose Miguel Fomento in 1802, until Gov-Gen Juan Antonio Martinez acquires it for a rest house. Photo: Main facade of the Malacañan Palace, ca 1920 (Leo Cloma Collection)

media_caption: Church of Santo Tomas de Villanueva in Miag-ao, Iloilo, 2013
media_credit: Photo by Betty Lalana and Lino Arboleda,Ortigas Foundation Library Collection
text_description: The Church of Santo Tomas de Villanueva in Miag-ao, Iloilo is completed with rococo morifs. It is declared World Heritage Site in 1993. Photo: Miag-ao Church, 2013 (Betty Lalana and Lino Arboleda, Ortigas Foundation Library)

media_caption: Exterior and bell tower of Vigan Cathedral, 2012
text_description: Vigan’s Cathedral of San Pablo is completed around this time. Photo: Exterior of the Cathedral of San Pablo and bell tower in Vigan City, 2012 (Arianne Buna)

media_caption: Tanjosoy-Bautista-de los Santos House in Malolos City, with art nouveau influence, 2017
text_description: The Tanjosoy-Bautista-De los Santos house in Malolos is built.

media_caption: Brick facade of the Church of Santa Monica in Sarrat, Ilocos Norte, 1995
media_credit: Photo by Betty Lalana and Lino Arboleda, Ortigas Foundation Library Collection
text_description: Before this year, Sarrat church, Ilocos Norte is completed. It will be rebuilt in 1848. Photo: Sarrat Church, 1995 (Betty Lalana and Lino Arboleda, Ortigas Foundation Library)

media_caption: Church of the Santisima Trinidad and bell tower, 2012
text_description: Loay’s Church of the Santisima Trinidad is built. The convento follows in 1838, the bell tower in 1865 and the cement portico façade in the early 20th century. Damaged by the 2013 earthquakes, the church is being restored. Photo: Loay Church, 2012 (Ric V. Obedencio)

media_caption: Osario or ossuary of Paco Cemetery, ca 1990
text_description: Built for the victims of a cholera epidemic, the oval-shaped Paco Cemetery in Manila is completed.

media_caption: Ceiling, facade, and bell tower of the Church of San Guillermo in Dalaguete, Cebu, 2003
media_credit: Photos by Betty Lalana and Lino Arboleda, Ortigas Foundation Library Collection
text_description: Dalaguete church in Cebu, begun in 1801, is completed. It has rococo altars.

media_caption: Church of San Miguel in Argao, Cebu, 2009
media_credit: Photo from National Historical Commission of the Philippines Collection
text_description: The Argao Church of San Miguel in Cebu, begun ca 1788, is completed. It has rococo altars. Photo: Rococo altar of Argao Church, ca 1990

media_caption: Prewar Cathedral of San Vitalis in Cebu City
text_description: The Cebu Cathedral (Church of San Vitalis), begun in 1734, is completed. It is damaged by World War II and reconstructed in 1959 by Jose Zaragosa. Photo: Prewar Church of San Vitalis (Leo Cloma Collection)

media_caption: NONE
text_description: The establishment of non-Spanish trading houses and businesses in the Philippines, especially in Binondo, Iloilo and Cebu, brings new construction materials and tools from Europe and the USA, such as fabric and stamped metal ceilings, zinc roofing from England, ice-boxes from USA, and French household bric-a-brac.

media_caption: Church of San Francisco de Asis in Naga, Cebu, 2013
text_description: Naga’s Church of San Francisco de Asis in Cebu is completed. Photo: Church of San Francisco de Asis, 2013 (Michael Ocaña)

media_caption: Mercado House in Bustos, Bulacan of carved stone, capiz windows, and wooden balustrade
text_description: The Mercado residence in Bustos, Bulacan is completed. Photo: Mercado House with carved stone, capiz windows, and wooden balustrade (Florentino Floro)

media_caption: Facade of the Palacio del Gobernador in Intramuros, Manila
media_credit: Photo from Fiestas en Manila Año 1825 by Justa Moreno Garbayo, Patrimonio Nacional, 1977
text_description: The façade of the Palacio del Gobernador in Intramuros (in photo), built under the governorship of Fausto Cruzat y Gongora, is renovated in the neoclassical style. It is ruined by an 1863 earthquake, then abandoned in 1880 after another earthquake. (Photo from Fiestas en Manila Año 1825 by Justa Moreno Garbayo, Patrimonio Nacional, 1977)

media_caption: Puente de Malagonlong
text_description: Puente de Malagonlong in Tayabas, Quezon, begun 1841 under Fr Antonio Mateo, OFM, is completed.

media_caption: Escuela Pia, popularly called Escolapia, 2017
text_description: The construction of the escuela pia at Taal, Batangas is completed. Photo: Escuela Pia, popularly called Escolapia, 2017 (Kiko del Rosario)

media_caption: Castillo de San Vicente Ferrer in Maribojoc, Bohol, 2016
media_credit: Photo by Claire Jabines, Bohol Provincial Tourism Office
article_title: Architecture 1860 Fort of San Vicente Ferrer
text_description: Punta Cruz’s Fort of San Vicente Ferrer in Maribojoc, Bohol is completed. Photo: Castillo de San Vicente Ferrer, 2016 (Claire Jabines, Bohol Provincial Tourism Office)

media_caption: NONE
text_description: The newly built façade of Santo Domingo in the neoclassical style, said to have been patterned after Christopher Wren’s St. Paul’s Cathedral in London, collapses. It stood for only a little over a year.

media_caption: Church of the Santo Niño in Tondo, Manila, 1993
media_credit: Photo by Betty Lalana and Lino Arboleda, Ortigas Foundation Library Collection
text_description: After 1863, the Tondo neoclassical church is completed, designed by Luciano Oliver. Photo: Church of the Santo Niño in Tondo, Manila, 1993 (Betty Lalana and Lino Arboleda, Ortigas Foundation Library)

media_caption: Casa Gorordo in the Parian, Cebu City, 2015
text_description: Fr Juan Isidro de Gorordo acquires a house in Parian, Cebu, built in the mid-19th century by Arch Alejandro Reynes. Acquired by Ramon Aboitiz Foundation, Inc. (RAFI) in 1983, it is now the Casa Gorordo house museum. Photo: Casa Gorordo, 2015 (RAFI)

media_caption: Church of Santa Ana in Molo, Iloilo, 2013
media_credit: Photo by Betty Lalana and Lino Arboleda, Ortigas Foundation Library Collection
text_description: The Molo Church of Santa Ana is substantially completed but work on the church interior continues to the 1920s when the neogothic retablos of the church are completed. It is marked by NHI in 1992. Photo: Molo Church, 2013 (Betty Lalana and Lino Arboleda, Ortigas Foundation Library)

media_caption: Aduana or Customs House, also Intendencia or City Administration in Intramuros, 1899
text_description: The Neo-classical Aduana in Intramuros, begun in 1832, is renovated 1874. It replaces the Alcaiceria de San Fernando in Binondo as the Customs House. Photo: Aduana or Customs House, also Intendencia or City Administration in Intramuros, 1899 (F. Tennyson Neely)

media_caption: Cathedral of Santa Isabel de Hungria in Jaro, Iloilo, 2015
text_description: Jaro cathedral dedicated to Santa Isabel de Hungria is completed, after Augustinians hand over the parish to Mariano Cuartero, named bishop of Jaro in 1867. Photo: Cathedral of Santa Isabel de Hungria, 2015 (Department of Tourism)

media_caption: Church of Santa Catalina de Alejandria in Carcar, Cebu, 2003
media_credit: Photo by Betty Lalana and Lino Arboleda, Ortigas Foundation Library Collection
text_description: Carcar church, Cebu, constructed under Fr. Antonio Manglano OSA, and begun in 1860, is completed under Fr Manuel Fernandez OSA. Photo: Carcar Church, 2003 (Betty Lalana and Lino Arboleda, Ortigas Foundation Library)

media_caption: Santos-Bautista House, 2017
text_description: The Santos-Bautista House with the caryatids in Malolos, Bulacan is completed. Photo: Santos-Bautista House, 2017 (Kiko del Rosario)

media_caption: Carcel de Cebu in Cebu City, 2015, now repurposed as a museum
media_credit: Photo from Ramon Aboitiz Foundation Inc Collection
text_description: The Carcel de Cebu, begun in 1863, is completed, designed by Domingo de Escondrillas.

media_caption: Church of San Miguel in Samboan, Cebu, 2009
media_credit: Photo by Betty Lalana and Lino Arboleda, Ortigas Foundation Library Collection
text_description: Samboan’s Church of San Miguel and Jacob’s Ladder in Cebu are completed. Photo: Church of San Miguel in Samboan, 2009 (Betty Lalana and Lino Arboleda, Ortigas Foundation Library)

media_caption: Basilica Minore of San Martin de Tours in Taal, Batangas, ca 1990
article_title: Architecture 1878 Taal church of San Martin
text_description: The Taal Church of San Martin in Batangas is completed, designed by municipal architect of Manila, Luciano Oliver. It is elevated to basilica minore on Oct 22, 1948. Restored in 1972, it is declared a National Shrine in 1974 by NHI.

media_caption: A section of Tabon Cave, 2015
text_description: Tabon Caves are inhabited by humans.

media_caption: The Manunggul Jar, 890 to 710 BC
media_credit: Photo from National Museum of the Philippines Collection
text_description: The human practice of secondary burial is indicated by the Manunggul Jar, found in the Tabon Caves, Palawan. Designated as a National Treasure by the National Museum of the Philippines, it depicts on its lid the human soul on a journey to the afterlife.

media_caption: Maitum jar
media_credit: Photo from National Museum of the Philippines Collection
text_description: In Maitum Cave, Saranggani, humans leave anthropomorphic burial jars, gall beads, bracelets, and other ornaments for the deceased.

media_caption: Balanghai CE 320, cabo negro, Ambangan, Libertad, Butuan, Agusan del Norte Province, northeastern Mindanao
text_description: Large edge-pegged plank boats popularly called “balanghay” are used for travel and residence. Discovered in the 1970s in Butuan City are the earliest dated boats found in the Philippines. (Photo by Roezielle Joy Iglesia)

media_caption: NONE
text_description: Ateneo Municipal builds a campus on Arsobispo and Anda Sts; it occupies the block until Santa Lucia.
